## Tips file hygiene

Any tip that is appended to
`agent/historical_experience/<gpu>/<op>/<backend>/tips.md` MUST honor this
rule:

- Do not record an F1–F4 pattern as a useful technique. If you discover one
  during a round, the round-level lesson is "this is benchmark over-fitting"
  and the lesson recorded in `tips.md` must say so explicitly.
- When recording legitimate weight-cache or scale-precompute techniques, state
  the **per-step real-training gain expectation**, not the benchmark number.

---

## Summary

| Pattern | Verdict | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Cache keyed on `id(activation)` | Forbidden | Activations are fresh tensors in real training |
| Cache keyed on `id(grad_out)` | Forbidden | `grad_out` from autograd is not a stable object |
| Cache keyed on `id(scale_of_activation)` | Forbidden | Chained on the activation cache, same failure mode |
| Cache keyed on `id(weight)` (with `_version` invalidation) | Allowed, but report per-step gain honestly |
| Single-kernel fusion that fuses two passes into one launch | Allowed |
| `ctx.save_for_backward` of forward-side intermediate that backward needs | Allowed |
| Kernel-level guard flag (e.g. `EVEN_K`) | Allowed |
| Layout-specialized kernel duplication | Allowed |
| `tl.dot_scaled` / block-scaled MFMA path | Allowed |

When in doubt, prefer kernel-side optimizations (autotune space, mfma variant,
tile shape, pipelining, scheduling) over wrapper-level caches. Kernel-side
gains transfer 1:1 to real training; wrapper-level caches almost never do.
